letic program is to continue in its mission  Both endowment and annual giving generate the operating support for VMI s athletic teams that allows coaches and staff to focus on developing cadets as athletes and leaders and to build competitive programs  Endowment and annual giving also provide grant in aid support to our cadet athletes  ScholarshipsGrant in aid support makes it possible for extraordinary young athletes to compete at the highest level of intercollegiate athletics while becoming extraordinary young leaders  OperationsSupport for athletic operations gives VMI s coaches and athletic staff the resources they need to help cadet athletes fully achieve their athletic and leadership potential  FacilitiesThe cadet athletes who proudly represent VMI   and the coaches and staff members who serve them   deserve the best possible facilities for practice and competition Tom Slater s Success Started with VMI FootballRead why Tom Slater gives to VMI Tom Slater s Success Started with VMI FootballRead why Tom Slater gives to VMI Tom Slater s Success Started with VMI FootballRead why Tom Slater gives to VMI Tom Slater s Success Started with VMI FootballRead why Tom Slater gives to VMI Tom Slater s Success Started with VMI FootballRead why Tom Slater gives to VMI  Tom Slater s Success Started with VMI FootballRead why Tom Slater gives to VMI Tom Slater s Success Started with VMI Football Read why Tom Slater gives to VMI  Support the Team On and Off the Field VMI athletics is about shaping character  competing honorably  and forging stronger bonds within the VMI family  Cadets are given the opportunity to compete at the highest level of intercollegiate athletics while broadening their horizons through VMI s extraordinary education  More than one quarter of the Corps of Cadets is a member of the Institute s 18 NCAA Division I teams  however  because the Institute is one of the smallest Division I institutions  it lacks the resources that large schools have  Generous privat